result.execSummary:
The defendant Natosha L Spears was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

records.addlTxt: for treatment (Incompetency).

Attorney Stanley V. Woodard in court for Defendant Natosha L Spears. Prosecuting Atty Adrienne E. Blais appeared for State of Wisconsin. Defendant Natosha L Spears not in court. Defendant was found not competent to proceed. After conversation with attorneys, Atty Woodard went to the CCB to attempt to speak with Ms Spears. Per DDA Viste, the defendant needs to appear in person at this hearing. 4:19pm - Defendant is now present along with her counsel Atty Stanley Woodard. Atty Adrienne Blais appears in court along with DDA Michelle Viste. Both sides stipulate to the findings of the psychologist. Atty Woodard spoke with his client and informed her of the commitment process. Questions of Ms Spears by the court. Ms Spears agrees that she's incompetent to proceed in this case at this time. Court made findings and finds the defendant is incompetent to proceed and ordered her committed to the DHS for treatment. These proceedings are suspended at this time. Reports are due every 3 months, except the last one is due in 2 months and then the competency hearing is to be held sometime within the last 30 days, unless she's found competent sooner.
